content.thinking:
Now I need to understand the retry_count mechanism. In the C code (main_d2/ai.cpp line 973):
```c
if ((ailp->retry_count) && !(Game_mode & GM_MULTI)) {
    ailp->consecutive_retries += ailp->retry_count;
    ailp->retry_count = 0;
```

The comment says "This is low level communication between systems of a sort that should not be done." - retry_count is set by the physics system when a robot has physics retries. It's not set by create_path_to_player.

So `retry_count` is set by the physics system (do_physics_sim). When a robot hits something and can't move, the physics system increments retry_count. Then do_ai_frame reads and processes it.


Since do_physics_sim is also OCaml-authoritative, I need to trace through how it manages retry_count and whether the OCaml version properly mirrors this behavior.

